# Loom — AI Knowledge Weaving Rules

You have access to a knowledge management system called **Loom** via MCP tools.
Follow these guidelines to proactively maintain a living knowledge base.

## When to WRITE (loom_weave)

Proactively call `loom_weave` when any of the following happen during our conversation:

- A system architecture or module boundary is defined or clarified
- A technical decision is made (and why)
- Business logic or domain rules are explained
- A non-obvious constraint or trade-off is identified
- A bug root cause is found and the fix approach is decided
- A feature design is finalized after discussion

**Categories:**

- `concepts` — architecture, modules, business logic, terminology
- `decisions` — ADR-style "why we chose X over Y" records
- `threads` — conversation summaries, meeting notes, discussion digests

**Modes:**

- `replace` — new entries or full rewrites (default)
- `append` — add new findings below existing content without losing it
- `section` — update a specific `## Heading` within an existing entry

## When to READ (loom_trace / loom_read)

- Always read `loom_index` first to get the global map
- Treat mandatory read set as required context:
  - Latest 5 entries (do not exclude threads)
  - Core concepts tagged `core`
- Mandatory snippets are truncated; call `loom_read` only when details are needed
- Before answering questions about the system, check if Loom already has relevant knowledge
- Before making architectural suggestions, trace existing decisions to avoid contradictions
- When the user asks "what do we know about X", always check Loom first
- Follow progressive disclosure:
  1) `loom_index` (global structure)
  2) `loom_trace` (retrieve candidate entries)
  3) `loom_read` (read full content only when needed)

## When to REFLECT (loom_reflect)

- When the user asks for a knowledge base health check
- Periodically after many weave operations to check for conflicts

## When to DEPRECATE (loom_deprecate)

- When new knowledge explicitly supersedes an older entry
- When a previous decision is reversed

## When to UPGRADE (loom_upgrade)

- When user says "帮我更新下 loom mcp" or asks to upgrade Loom itself
- First run `loom_upgrade` with `dryRun=true` when unsure
- Then run `loom_upgrade` without dryRun to perform actual upgrade

## When to UPDATE CHANGELOG (loom_changelog)

- After core feature upgrades are completed
- Use `mode=auto` to infer daily highlights from git commits
- If auto misses key points, use `mode=manual` with explicit highlights

## Mandatory Closeout Rule (REQUIRED)

- After finishing a feature and passing build/lint, you MUST run closeout:
  1) call `loom_weave` (or `loom-cli closeout`) to record a thread/concept summary
  2) call `loom_changelog(mode=auto)` to update public daily highlights
- Do not end implementation turn without these two steps unless user explicitly says skip

## General Rules

- Always include meaningful tags for better retrieval
- For foundational concepts, include `core` tag (or set `is_core=true`)
- Keep entries focused: one topic per entry
- Prefer structured Markdown with `##` headings
- For threads: summarize key points, don't dump raw conversation
